{"parse":{"title":"at","pageid":3964,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Appendix:Variations of \"at\"}}\n{{minitoc}}\n==English==\n{{wp|AT}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{a|en|strong form}}:\n** {{IPA|en|/æt/}}\n** {{audio|en|en-us-at.ogg|a=US}}\n** {{rhymes|en|æt|s=1}}\n* {{a|en|weak form}}:\n** {{IPA|en|/ət/}}\n** {{hmp|en|it<q:some accents>}}\n* {{hyph|en|at}}\n* {{hmp|en|@}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{etymon|en|id=on|:inh|enm:at<id:on>|tree=1}}\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|at}}, from {{inh|en|ang|æt|t=at, near, by, toward}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*at}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*at|t=at, near, to}}, from {{inh|en|ine-pro|*h₂éd|t=near, at}}. Cognate with {{cog|sco|at|t=at}}, {{cog|frr|äät}}, {{m|frr|äit}}, {{m|frr|et}}, {{m|frr|it|t=at}}, {{cog|da|at|t=to}}, {{cog|sv|åt|t=for, toward}}, {{cog|no|åt|t=to}}, {{cog|fo|at|t=at, to, toward}}, {{cog|is|að|t=to, towards}}, {{cog|got|𐌰𐍄|t=at}}, {{cog|la|ad|t=to, near}}.\n\n====Preposition====\n{{en-head|prep}}\n\n# [[in|In]], [[near]], or in the general vicinity of (a particular [[place]]).\n#: {{ux|en|Caesar was '''at''' Rome.}}\n#: {{ux|en|A climate treaty was signed '''at''' Kyoto in 1997.}}\n#: {{ux|en|I was '''at''' Jim’s house '''at''' the corner of Fourth Street and Vine.}}\n#: {{co|en|'''at''' the bottom of the page; sitting '''at''' the table; '''at''' church; '''at''' sea}}\n#* '''1919''', Plutarch, [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Cicero*.html “The Life of Cicero”] in ''Parallel Lives'', 43 (Bernadotte Perrin, trans.):\n#*: Hirtius and Pansa, who were good men and admirers of Cicero, begged him not to desert them, and undertook to put down Antony if Cicero would remain '''at''' Rome.\n#* {{RQ:Schuster Hepaticae|volume=V|page=4|text=(''b'') sporophyte with foot reduced, the entire sporophyte enveloped by the calyptra, which is ± stipitate '''at''' the base.}}\n#* '''2016''', [https://web.archive.org/web/20170930001420/https://learningenglish.voanews.com/a/lets-learn-english-lesson-5-where-are-you/3168971.html VOA Learning English] (public domain):\n#*: Today my friend Marsha is '''at''' her friend’s house.\n## Attending (an educational institution).\n##: {{ux|en|She's '''at''' Oxford University, studying chemistry.}}\n## Working for (a company) or in (a place or situation).\n##: {{ux|en|He used to be '''at''' Lehman Brothers. Now he's '''at''' Merrill Lynch.}}\n##: {{ux|en|'Where does he work?' — 'I think he's still '''at''' the solicitors.'}}\n## {{n-g|Indicating distance or direction relative to the speaker.}}\n##: {{ux|en|Target '''at''' five miles. Prepare torpedoes.}}\n##: {{ux|en|Look out! UFO '''at''' two o'clock!}}\n# Present or taking place during (an event).\n#: {{ux|en|Was he '''at''' the meeting?}}\n#: {{ux|en|There was a big fight '''at''' the class reunion.}}\n# {{senseid|en|indicating time}} {{n-g|Indicating time of occurrence, especially an instant of time, or a period of time relatively short in context or from the speaker’s perspective.}}\n#: {{co|en|'''at''' six o’clock; '''at''' dawn; '''at''' closing time; '''at''' the age of twelve; '''at''' night; [[at the moment|'''at''' the moment]]}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1838|title=The Family Magazine| passage=Lafayette was major-general in the American army '''at''' the age of 18 {{...}}}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=April 19, 2012|author=Josh Halliday|work=the Guardian| title=[http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/2012/apr/19/free-speech-haven-lawless-cesspool Free speech haven or lawless cesspool – can the internet be civilised?]| passage=Other global taboos, such as sex and suicide, manifest themselves widely online, with websites offering suicide guides and Hot XXX Action seconds away '''at''' the click of a button. The UK government will come under pressure to block access to pornographic websites this year when a committee of MPs publishes its report on protecting children online.}}\n#* '''2016''', [https://web.archive.org/web/20171030003034/https://learningenglish.voanews.com/a/lets-learn-english-lesson-8-are-you-busy/3253185.html VOA Learning English] (public domain)\n#*: Hi, Anne. Are you busy? &mdash; Hi, Anna. Yes. '''At''' 10 a.m. I am writing.\n#* {{quote-journal|en|journal=w:TIME|title=The Danger of Surrendering Your Financial Independence in a Relationship|date=April 22 2026|author=Jillian Sanders\n|text='''At''' 21, I moved to New York City to pursue acting.\n|url=https://time.com/article/2026/04/17/the-danger-of-surrendering-your-financial-independence-in-a-relationship/\n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20260422181713/https://time.com/article/2026/04/17/the-danger-of-surrendering-your-financial-independence-in-a-relationship/}}\n## {{lb|en|UK|Commonwealth|Ireland|especially|finance|and|law}} {{q|also '''as at'''; before dates}} [[on|On]] (a particular date).\n##* '''n.d.''', quoted in ''Longmans Business Dictionary'':\n##*: balance '''as at''' 20th March 1999\n##* {{quote-web|en|text='''at''' the date of the commencement of the proceedings before the judicial or administrative authority of the Contracting State where the child is|title=Convention of 25 October 1980 on the Civil Aspects of International Child Abduction|url=https://www.hcch.net/en/instruments/conventions/full-text/?cid=24|date=1980-10-25|work=Hague Conference on Private International Law}}\n# In the [[direction#Noun|direction]] of; towards; ({{n-g|often implied to be in a [[hostile]] or [[careless]] manner}}).\n#: {{ux|en|Don’t just [[talk at|talk '''at''']] someone; really listen to what they have to say.}}\n#: {{ux|en|Stones were thrown '''at''' us, but we couldn't see who did.}}\n#: {{ux|en|He shouted '''at''' her.}}\n#: {{ux|en|She pointed '''at''' the curious animal.}}\n#* {{RQ:Ferguson Zollenstein|IV| passage=“My Continental prominence is improving,” I commented dryly. <br> Von Lindowe cut '''at''' a furze bush with his silver-mounted rattan. <br> “Quite so,” he said as dryly, his hand at his mustache. “I may say if your intentions were known your life would not be worth a curse.”}}\n#* {{quote-av|en|title=[[w:Barbie (film)|Barbie]]|actor=w:Ryan Gosling|role=[[w:Ken (doll)|Ken]]|date=9 July 2023|text=Come on in. I’ll play the guitar '''at''' you.}}\n# {{n-g|Indicating action bearing upon something, especially continued or repeated action.}}\n#: {{ux|en|Don't pick '''at''' your food!}}\n#: {{ux|en|My cat keeps scratching '''at''' the furniture.}}\n#: {{ux|en|I was working '''at''' the problem all day.}}\n# In response or reaction to.\n#: {{ux|en|'''At''' my request, they agreed to move us to another hotel.}}\n#: {{ux|en|He jumped '''at''' the sudden noise.}}\n#: {{ux|en|We laughed '''at''' the joke.}}\n#: {{ux|en|She was mad '''at''' their comments.}}\n# [[occupy|Occupied]] in (activity).\n#: {{co|en|men '''at''' work; children '''at''' play}}\n# In a state of.\n#: {{ux|en|The two countries are '''at''' war.}}\n#: {{ux|en|She is [[at sixes and sevens|'''at''' sixes and sevens]] with him.}}\n#: {{ux|en|They are [[at loggerheads|'''at''' loggerheads]] over how best to tackle the fiscal cliff.}}\n# Subject to.\n#: {{ux|en|We hope that the event will go ahead, but we are '''at''' the whim of the weather.}}\n#: {{ux|en|The city was [[at the mercy of|'''at''' the mercy of]] the occupying forces.}}\n# {{senseid|en|price}} {{n-g|Denotes a price.}}\n#: {{ux|en|3 apples '''at''' 2¢ (each)}}\n#: {{ux|en|The offer was '''at''' $30,000 before negotiations.}}\n# {{non-gloss|Indicates a position on a scale or in a series.}}\n#: {{ux|en|Sell '''at''' $90.}}\n#: {{ux|en|Tiger finished the round '''at''' tenth, seven strokes behind the leaders.}}\n#: {{ux|en|I’m offering it—just to select customers—[[at cost|'''at''' cost]].}}\n#: {{ux|en|The river is '''at''' its highest in spring.}}\n#: {{ux|en|These babies weigh in '''at''' ten tons apiece.}}\n#: {{ux|en|[[at best|'''at''' best]]; [[at most|'''at''' most]]; [[at worst|'''at''' worst]]; [[at least|'''at''' least]]}}\n# {{n-g|In certain phrases<!-- unless anyone can demonstrate general productive use -->, used to indicate the manner in which something happens or is done.}}\n#: {{ux|en|The car came towards me '''at''' speed.}}\n#: {{ux|en|He spoke '''at''' great length on the topic.}}\n#: {{ux|en|The winner will be chosen '''at''' random.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2012|author=Sami Moubayed|title=Syria and the USA: Washington's Relations with Damascus|isbn=0857730673|passage=A few days later, on 1 October, King Hussein opened the Jordanian Parliament by speaking '''at''' length about the crisis in Syria,}}\n# {{n-g|Indicates a specific [[speed]] or [[rate#English|rate]] that is maintained by something.}}\n#: {{ux|en|We were cruising along '''at''' well over the speed limit of fifty miles per hour.}}\n#: {{ux|en|It is growing '''at''' the rate of 3% a year.}}\n# {{n-g|Indicates a means or method.}}\n#: {{ux|en|'How was the painting sold?' — ''''At''' auction.'}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1995|author=Richard Klein|title=Cigarettes are Sublime|isbn=0822316412|page=41|passage={{...}} to be sold '''at''' auction for sixty gold francs.}}\n# {{lb|en|used for skills (including in activities) or areas of knowledge}} On the [[subject]] of; [[regarding]].\n#: {{ux|en|The twins were both bad '''at''' chemistry.}}\n#: {{ux|en|He slipped '''at''' marksmanship over his extended holiday.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2015|title=Sanyan Stories: Favorites from a Ming Dynasty Collection|page=157|isbn=0295805692\n|passage=She’s good '''at''' playing musical instruments, singing and dancing, chess, calligraphy, and painting.}}\n# {{lb|en|Ireland|stressed pronunciation}} Bothering, irritating, causing discomfort to\n#* '''1995''' Keith Wood, quoted in David Hughes, \"[http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/rugby-union-wood-oddson-to-take-one-against-the-head-1568622.html Wood odds-on to take one against the head]\", in ''The Independent'' (London) 18 January:\n#*: I think ‘Jesus, my back is '''at''' me’. Then I get the ball. Off you go for 10 yards and you don’t feel a thing. Then you stop and think: ‘Jesus, it’s '''at''' me again’[.]\n#* '''2014''' Marian Keyes \"[https://web.archive.org/web/20140203045758/http://www.mariankeyes.com/newsletter/January2014-2?forumboardid=26&forumtopicid=26 Antarctic Diary - Part 2]\" personal website (January 2014):\n#*: He seems to be saying. “Ah, go on, you’re making the other lads feel bad.” But the 4th fella says, “No. Don’t be '''‘at’''' me. I’m just not in the form right now, I’ll stay where I am, thanks.”\n# {{n-g|Also used in various other idiomatic combinations: '''[[at a pinch]]''', '''[[at all]]''', '''[[at fault]]''', '''[[at pains]]''', '''[[at risk]]''', '''[[at that]]''', etc.; see the individual entries.}}\n\n=====Usage notes=====\n* ''He threw the ball to me'' &mdash; (so I could catch it).\n* ''He threw the ball at me'' &mdash; (trying to hit me with it).\n* ''He talked to her'' &mdash; (conversationally).\n* ''He shouted at her'' &mdash; (aggressively).\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col4|en|where it's at|at bank|atmark|atone|atonement|Atwater|eat away at|hereat|thereat|whereat}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|in or very near a particular place}}{{multitrans|data=\n* Albanian: {{tt|sq|në}}\n* Arabic: {{tt+|ar|عِنْد}}\n*: Egyptian Arabic: {{tt|arz|عند|tr=ʕand}}\n*: Hijazi Arabic: {{t|acw|عِنْد|tr=ʕind}}\n* Belarusian: {{tt|be|у}}, {{tt|be|ў}}, {{tt|be|пры}}, {{tt|be|каля́}}\n* Breton: {{tt+|br|e}}\n* Bulgarian: {{tt+|bg|при}}, {{tt+|bg|до}}, {{tt+|bg|на}}, {{tt+|bg|у}}\n* Burmese: {{tt+|my|မှာ}}, {{tt+|my|၌}}\n* Catalan: {{tt+|ca|a}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Cantonese: {{tt+|yue|喺}} {{qualifier|vernacular}}, {{tt|yue|在}} {{qualifier|formal}}\n*: Mandarin: {{tt+|cmn|在}}\n* Czech: {{tt+|cs|u}}, {{tt+|cs|při}}\n* Danish: {{tt+|da|på}}\n* Dutch: {{tt+|nl|op}}, {{tt+|nl|bij}}\n* Esperanto: {{tt+|eo|ĉe}}\n* Estonian: {{t-needed|et}}\n* Faroese: {{tt+|fo|í}}, {{tt+|fo|á}}, {{tt+|fo|hjá}}, {{tt|fo|til}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|-lla}}, {{tt+|fi|-llä}} {{qualifier|adessive case}}, {{tt+|fi|-ssa}}, {{tt+|fi|-ssä}} {{qualifier|inessive case}}, {{q|genetive +}} {{tt+|fi|luona}}, {{q|genetive +}} {{tt+|fi|tykönä}}\n* French: {{tt+|fr|à}}, {{tt+|fr|en}}\n* Galician: {{tt+|gl|en}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|an}}, {{tt+|de|auf}}, {{tt+|de|bei}}, {{tt+|de|in}}, {{tt+|de|zu}}\n* Gothic: {{tt|got|𐌰𐍄}}\n* Greek: {{tt+|el|στον|m}}, {{tt+|el|στη|f}}, {{tt+|el|στο|n}}, {{tt+|el|στους|m-p}}, {{tt+|el|στις|f-p}}, {{tt+|el|στα|n-p}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{t-needed|grc}}\n* Hebrew: {{tt+|he|אֵצֶל|tr='étsel}}\n* Hindi: {{tt+|hi|पर}}, {{tt+|hi|में}}, {{tt+|hi|से}}\n* Hungarian: {{tt+|hu|-n}}, {{tt+|hu|-on}}, {{tt+|hu|-en}}, {{tt+|hu|-ön}} {{qualifier|superessive case}}, {{tt+|hu|-nál}}, {{tt+|hu|-nél}} {{qualifier|adessive case}}\n* Icelandic: {{tt+|is|í}}, {{tt+|is|á}}\n* Ido: {{tt+|io|ye}}\n* Igbo: {{t-needed|ig}}\n* Indonesian: {{t-needed|id}}\n* Interlingua: {{tt+|ia|a}}, {{tt+|ia|apud}}, {{tt+|ia|in}}\n* Irish: {{tt|ga|ag}}\n* Italian: {{tt+|it|a}}, {{tt+|it|in}}\n* Japanese: {{tt+|ja|で|tr=...de|alt=...で}}, {{tt+|ja|に|tr=...ni|alt=... に}}\n* Korean: {{tt+|ko|에서|alt=...에서}}, {{tt+|ko|에|alt=...에}}\n* Kurdish:\n*: Central Kurdish: {{tt+|ckb|لە}}\n*: Northern Kurdish: {{tt+|kmr|li}}\n* Ladin: {{t-needed|lld}}\n* Ladino: {{t-needed|lad}}\n* Lao: {{tt|lo|ທີ່}}\n* Latgalian: {{tt|ltg|pi}}\n* Latin: ''[[locative case]]'', {{tt+|la|ad}}, {{tt+|la|apud}}\n* Latvian: {{tt+|lv|pie}}\n* Lithuanian: ''[[locative case]]'', {{tt+|lt|pas}}, {{t|lt|prie}}\n* Macedonian: {{tt|mk|во}}, {{tt|mk|на}}, {{tt|mk|кај}}, {{tt|mk|при}}\n* Malay: {{tt+|ms|di}}, {{tt+|ms|dekat}} {{qualifier|informal}}\n* Maltese: {{t-needed|mt}}\n* Manchu: {{tt|mnc|ᡩᡝ}}\n* Māori: {{tt+|mi|i}} {{qualifier|in the past}}, {{tt|mi|kei}} {{qualifier|present time}}, {{tt|mi|hei}} {{qualifier|for future events}}, {{tt|mi|a}} {{qualifier|for future events}}\n* Mon: {{tt|mnw|ပ္ဍဲ|tr=pḍay}}\n* Navajo: {{tt|nv|-di}}, {{tt|nv|-gi}}\n* Neapolitan: {{tt|nap|a}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{tt+|nb|på}}\n*: Nynorsk: {{tt|nn|på}}\n* Occitan: {{t+|oc|a}}, {{t+|oc|en}}\n* Persian: {{tt+|fa|در|tr=dar}}\n* Polabian: {{tt|pox|ai̯}}, {{tt|pox|au̯}}\n* Polish: {{tt+|pl|w}}, {{tt+|pl|u}}, {{tt+|pl|przy}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt+|pt|em}} (not distinct from the senses expressed in English by ''in'' or ''on''), {{tt+|pt|por}}, {{tt+|pt|a}} (unproductive; only used with a few words, as in ''à mesa'': at the table)\n* Rapa Nui: {{tt|rap|i}}\n* Romani: {{tt|rom|kaj}}\n* Romanian: {{tt+|ro|la}}\n* Russian: {{tt+|ru|в}}, {{tt+|ru|на}}, {{tt+|ru|у}}, {{tt+|ru|во́зле}}\n* Sardinian: {{t|sc|a}}, {{t|sc|in}}\n* Slovak: {{tt+|sk|v}}, {{tt|sk|pri}}, {{tt+|sk|na}}\n* Slovene: {{tt+|sl|pri}}, {{tt+|sl|na}}, {{tt+|sl|ob}}\n* Sorbian:\n*: Lower Sorbian: {{tt|dsb|wu}}, {{tt|dsb|pśi}}\n* Spanish: {{tt+|es|en}}\n* Sundanese: {{tt+|su|dina}}\n* Swahili: {{tt|sw|karibu na}}\n* Swedish: {{tt+|sv|på}}, {{tt+|sv|vid}}\n* Tamil: {{t|ta|-இல்}}\n* Telugu: {{tt+|te|వద్ద}}\n* Thai: {{tt+|th|ที่}}\n* Tibetan: {{tt|bo|ལ}}\n* Tok Pisin: {{tt|tpi|long}}\n* Turkish: {{tt+|tr|-da}}, {{tt+|tr|-de}}\n* Ukrainian: {{tt+|uk|у}}, {{tt+|uk|в}}, {{tt+|uk|при}}, {{tt+|uk|біля́}}\n* Veps: {{t-needed|vep}}\n* Vietnamese: {{tt|vi|ở tại}}, {{tt+|vi|lúc}}, {{tt+|vi|vào}}, {{tt+|vi|ở}}\n* Volapük: {{tt+|vo|pö}}\n* Võro: {{t-needed|vro}}\n* Votic: ''adessive case'', ''inessive case''\n* Walloon: {{tt+|wa|a}}\n* Welsh: {{sense|in}} {{tt+|cy|yn|id=in}}, {{tt+|cy|mewn}}; {{sense|near}} {{tt|cy|wrth}}, {{tt+|cy|ger}}\n* Woiwurrung: {{t|wyi|jeyou}}\n* Zealandic: {{tt|zea|bie}}, {{tt|zea|in}}, {{tt|zea|nessens}} {{q|alongside}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|indicating time}}\n* Albanian: {{tt|sq|në}}\n* Arabic: {{tt+|ar|فِي}}, {{tt+|ar|عِنْدَ}}\n*: Egyptian Arabic: {{tt|arz|في|tr=fi}}\n*: Hijazi Arabic: {{t|acw|في|tr=fi}}\n* Breton: {{tt+|br|da}}\n* Bulgarian: {{tt+|bg|в}}, {{tt+|bg|във}}, {{tt+|bg|на}}, {{tt+|bg|през}}\n* Burmese: {{tt+|my|မှာ}}, {{tt+|my|၌}}\n* Catalan: {{tt+|ca|a}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{qualifier|no preposition is used, e.g.:}} {{tt|cmn|[[五]][[點鐘]]}} or {{tt|cmn|[[五]][[點]]|lit=at five o'clock}}\n* Cornish: {{tt|kw|dhe}}\n* Czech: {{tt+|cs|v}}\n* Danish: {{tt+|da|på}}\n* Dutch: {{tt+|nl|om}}\n* Esperanto: {{tt+|eo|je}}\n* Estonian: {{t-needed|et}}\n* Faroese: {{t-needed|fo}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|-lta}}, {{tt+|fi|-ltä}} {{qualifier|ablative case}}, {{tt+|fi|-na}}, {{tt+|fi|-nä}} {{qualifier|essive case}}\n* French: {{tt+|fr|à}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|um}}\n* Gothic: {{tt|got|𐌰𐍄}}\n* Greek: {{tt+|el|στον|m}}, {{tt+|el|στη|f}}, {{tt+|el|στο|n}}, {{tt+|el|στους|m-p}}, {{tt+|el|στις|f-p}}, {{tt+|el|στα|n-p}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{t-needed|grc}}\n* Hungarian: {{tt+|hu|-kor}} {{qualifier|temporalis case}}\n* Icelandic: {{tt+|is|á}}, {{tt+|is|í}}\n* Igbo: {{t-needed|ig}}\n* Indonesian: {{t-needed|id}}\n* Interlingua: {{tt+|ia|a}}\n* Irish: {{t|ga|ag}}, {{t|ga|ar}}\n* Italian: {{tt+|it|a}} {{qualifier|+ definite article}}\n* Japanese: {{tt+|ja|に|tr=...ni|alt=...に}}\n* Korean: {{tt+|ko|에|alt=...에}}\n* Kurdish:\n*: Central Kurdish: {{tt+|ckb|لە}}\n*: Northern Kurdish: {{tt+|kmr|li}}\n* Ladin: {{t-needed|lld}}\n* Ladino: {{t-needed|lad}}\n* Latin: ''[[ablative]] case''\n* Latvian: {{t-needed|lv}}\n* Lithuanian: {{t-needed|lt}}\n* Macedonian: {{tt|mk|во}}\n* Malay: {{tt+|ms|pada}}\n* Maltese: {{tt|mt|fi}}\n* Manchu: {{tt|mnc|ᡩᡝ}}\n* Mòcheno: {{tt|mhn|um}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{t-needed|nb}}\n*: Nynorsk: {{t-needed|nn}}\n* Polish: {{tt+|pl|o}}, {{tt+|pl|w}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt+|pt|a}}\n* Romanian: {{tt+|ro|la}}\n* Russian: {{tt+|ru|в}}\n* Slovak: {{tt+|sk|o}}\n* Slovene: {{tt+|sl|ob}}\n* Spanish: {{tt+|es|a}}, {{t+|es|ad}} {{qualifier|dated}}\n* Swahili: {{t-needed|sw}}\n* Swedish: {{tt+|sv|vid}}\n* Tamil: {{t|ta|-கு}}, {{t|ta|-இல்}}\n* Ukrainian: {{tt+|uk|о}}\n* Veps: {{t-needed|vep}}\n* Vietnamese: {{tt+|vi|lúc}}\n* Volapük: {{tt+|vo|tü}}\n* Võro: {{t-needed|vro}}\n* Votic: ''adessive case''\n* Walloon: {{tt+|wa|a}}\n* Welsh: {{tt+|cy|am}}, {{tt+|cy|ar}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|in the direction of}}\n* Albanian: {{tt|sq|në}}\n* Arabic: {{tt|ar|صَوْب}}\n*: Egyptian Arabic: {{tt|arz|ناحية|tr=naḥyet}}\n* Bulgarian: {{tt+|bg|при}}, {{tt+|bg|на}}, {{tt|bg|по вре́ме на}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{tt+|cmn|在}}\n* Czech: {{tt+|cs|na}}, {{tt+|cs|do}}\n* Danish: {{tt+|da|til}}\n* Dutch: {{tt+|nl|op}}, {{tt+|nl|naar}}\n* Esperanto: {{tt+|eo|al}}\n* Estonian: {{t-needed|et}}\n* Faroese: {{tt|fo|eftir}} {{q|dative case}}\n* Finnish: {{tt|fi|-Vn}} {{qualifier|illative case}}, {{tt+|fi|-lle}} {{qualifier|allative case}}, {{tt+|fi|kohti}}\n* French: {{tt+|fr|vers}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|nach}}, {{tt+|de|zu}}\n* Greek: {{tt+|el|στον|m}}, {{tt+|el|στη|f}}, {{tt+|el|στο|n}}, {{tt+|el|στους|m-p}}, {{tt+|el|στις|f-p}}, {{tt+|el|στα|n-p}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{t-needed|grc}}\n* Hungarian: {{tt+|hu|-t}} {{qualifier|accusative case}}\n* Icelandic: {{tt+|is|að}}, {{tt+|is|til}}\n* Igbo: {{t-needed|ig}}\n* Indonesian: {{t-needed|id}}\n* Interlingua: {{tt+|ia|a}}\n* Irish: {{tt|ga|ag}}\n* Italian: {{tt+|it|a}}\n* Japanese: {{tt+|ja|に|tr=...ni|alt=...に}}, {{tt+|ja|を|tr=...o|alt=...を}}\n* Korean: {{tt+|ko|에게|alt=...에게}}, {{tt+|ko|로|alt=...로}}, {{tt|ko|에게로|alt=...에게로}}\n* Kurdish:\n*: Central Kurdish: {{tt+|ckb|لە}}\n*: Northern Kurdish: {{tt+|kmr|li}}\n* Ladin: {{t-needed|lld}}\n* Ladino: {{t-needed|lad}}\n* Lao: {{t-needed|lo}}\n* Latin: {{tt+|la|ad}}\n* Latvian: {{t-needed|lv}}\n* Lithuanian: {{t-needed|lt}}\n* Macedonian: {{tt|mk|во}}, {{tt|mk|на}}\n* Maltese: {{t-needed|mt}}\n* Manchu: {{tt|mnc|ᡩᡝ}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{tt+|nb|på}}\n*: Nynorsk: {{tt|nn|på}}\n* Polish: {{tt+|pl|na}}, {{tt+|pl|do}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt+|pt|em}}\n* Romanian: {{tt+|ro|înspre}}, {{tt+|ro|spre}}\n* Russian: {{tt+|ru|в}}, {{tt+|ru|на}}\n* Slovak: {{tt+|sk|do}}\n* Slovene: {{t-needed|sl}}\n* Spanish: {{tt+|es|a}}\n* Swahili: {{t-needed|sw}}\n* Swedish: {{tt+|sv|på}}, {{tt+|sv|mot}}\n* Tamil: {{t|ta|-இடம்}}, {{t|ta|-ஐ}}\n* Thai: {{tt+|th|ณ}}\n* Tok Pisin: {{tt|tpi|long}}\n* Veps: {{t-needed|vep}}\n* Volapük: {{t-needed|vo}}\n* Võro: {{t-needed|vro}}\n* Votic: ''illative case'', {{t|vot|poolõ}}\n* Walloon: {{tt+|wa|a}}\n* Welsh: {{tt+|cy|at}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|denoting a price}}\n* Albanian: {{t-needed|sq}}\n* Catalan: {{tt+|ca|a}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|za}}\n* Danish: {{t-needed|da}}\n* Dutch: {{tt+|nl|voor}}, {{tt+|nl|tegen}}\n* Estonian: {{t-needed|et}}\n* Faroese: {{t-needed|fo}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|à}} {{q|unit price}}\n* French: {{tt+|fr|à}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|zu}}, {{tt+|de|für}}\n* Greek: ''periphrastically''\n*: Ancient Greek: {{t-needed|grc}}\n* Hungarian: {{t-needed|hu}}\n* Icelandic: {{tt+|is|á}}, {{tt+|is|í}}\n* Igbo: {{t-needed|ig}}\n* Indonesian: {{t-needed|id}}\n* Irish: {{t|ga|ag}}, {{t|ga|ar}}\n* Italian: {{tt+|it|a}}, {{tt+|it|di}}\n* Korean: {{tt+|ko|에|alt=...에}}\n* Ladin: {{t-needed|lld}}\n* Ladino: {{t-needed|lad}}\n* Latin: {{t-needed|lla}}\n* Latvian: {{t-needed|lv}}\n* Lithuanian: {{t-needed|lt}}\n* Maltese: {{t-needed|mt}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{t-needed|nb}}\n*: Nynorsk: {{t-needed|nn}}\n* Polish: {{tt+|pl|za}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt+|pt|por}}, {{tt+|pt|a}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|по}}\n* Slovak: {{tt+|sk|za}}\n* Slovene: {{t-needed|sl}}\n* Spanish: {{tt+|es|a}}\n* Swahili: {{t-needed|sw}}\n* Swedish: {{tt+|sv|för}}, {{tt+|sv|à}} {{q|each}}\n* Tamil: {{t|ta|-இல்}}\n* Veps: {{t-needed|vep}}\n* Volapük: {{t-needed|vo}}\n* Võro: {{t-needed|vro}}\n* Votic: ''elative case''\n* Welsh: {{tt+|cy|am}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|occupied in (activity)}}\n* Albanian: {{t-needed|sq}}\n* Czech: {{t-needed|cs}}\n* Danish: {{t-needed|da}}\n* Dutch: {{tt+|nl|aan}}\n* Estonian: {{t-needed|et}}\n* Faroese: {{t-needed|fo}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|-ssa}}, {{tt+|fi|-ssä}} {{qualifier|inessive case}}; {{qualifier|+ genitive}} {{tt+|fi|parissa}}\n* French: {{tt+|fr|à}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|bei}}\n* Greek: ''periphrastically''\n*: Ancient Greek: {{t-needed|grc}}\n* Hungarian: {{t-needed|hu}}\n* Icelandic: {{tt+|is|við}}, {{tt+|is|í}}, {{tt+|is|á}}\n* Igbo: {{t-needed|ig}}\n* Indonesian: {{t-needed|id}}\n* Irish: {{t|ga|ag}}\n* Italian: {{tt+|it|a}}\n* Ladin: {{t-needed|lld}}\n* Ladino: {{t-needed|lad}}\n* Latin: {{t-needed|lla}}\n* Latvian: {{t-needed|lv}}\n* Lithuanian: {{t-needed|lt}}\n* Maltese: {{t-needed|mt}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{t-needed|nb}}\n*: Nynorsk: {{t-needed|nn}}\n* Polish: {{tt+|pl|w}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt+|pt|a}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|в}}\n* Slovak: {{t-needed|sk}}\n* Slovene: {{t-needed|sl}}\n* Spanish: {{t-needed|es}}\n* Swahili: {{t-needed|sw}}\n* Swedish: {{tt+|sv|i}}\n* Tamil: {{t|ta|-இல்}}\n* Veps: {{t-needed|vep}}\n* Volapük: {{t-needed|vo}}\n* Võro: {{t-needed|vro}}\n* Votic: ''inessive case''\n}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|in response or reaction to}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|ante}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|sign}} The [[at sign]] ([[@]]).\n\n=====Usage notes=====\n*Can sometimes be used between [[Unsupported_titles/`lsqb`_`rsqb`|square brackets]] in substitution of [[@]] in emails\n**''jon.smith[at]example.com'' or ''jon.smith [at] example.com''\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-see|at sign}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|informal|neologism}} {{rare form of|en|@}}; to reply to or talk to someone, either online or face-to-face. {{q|from the practice of targeting a message or reply to someone online by writing @''name''}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=2022|author=William Morris|title=Motley Vision\n|passage=If you have questions or observations on my discussion questions, feel free to reply to this email, '''at''' me on Twitter, or comment on the companion post on AMV.}}\n\n=====Usage notes=====\n* Chiefly used in the phrase \"don't @ me\"/\"don't at me\". It can be used humorously when stated after an unpopular or ironic opinion, in order to forestall dissent.\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Pronoun====\n{{en-pron}}\n\n# {{lb|en|Northern England|rare|possibly|obsolete}} {{alt form|en|'at|pos=relative pronoun; reduced form of “that” and/or “what”}}.\n#* '''1860''', Robert Gordon Latham, ''Song of Solomon'', as spoken in Durham [by Thomas Moore<!--according to the book-->], in ''A  hand-book of the English language'':\n#*: Tak us t’ foxes, t’ little foxes '''at''' spoils t’ veynes: fer our veynes hev tender grapes.\n\n===Etymology 3===\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun|s|*}}\n\n# {{alt form|en|att}} {{gloss|Laos currency unit}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:OneLook}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=at|T&A|T.A.|T/A|TA|ta}}\n\n{{cln|en|2-letter words}}\n\n==Albanian==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{bor+|sq|ota|آت|tr=at|t=horse}}.<ref>{{R:sq:Meyer|at {{...}} 2)|20}}</ref><ref>{{R:sq:Bufli-Rocchi|pages=48–49}}</ref>\n\n===Noun===\n{{sq-noun|m|head=át|atllárë|áti}}\n\n# [[saddle horse]], [[steed]] {{C|sq|Horses}}\n#: {{par|sq|kálë|hamshór}}\n# {{lb|sq|figurative}} strong [[hard-working]] man\n#: {{syn|sq|farán}}\n\n====Declension====\n{{sq-noun-m|llarë}}\n\n===References===\n<references/>\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:sq:Fjalorthi}}\n* {{R:sq:FGSS}}\n* {{R:sq:Jungg:1895|at|2*}}\n\n==Azerbaijani==\n{{az-variant|ат|آت}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|az|/ɑt/}}\n* {{audio|az|LL-Q9292 (aze)-Zardabi Bakuvi-at.wav|a=Baku}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{inh|az|trk-pro|*at||horse}}.<ref>{{R:trk-pro:SDM|*ăt|855}}</ref>\n\n====Noun====\n{{az-noun}}\n\n# [[horse]] {{c|az|Horses}}\n# {{lb|az|chess}} [[knight]]\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{az-decl-noun|a|c}}\n\n====See also====\n{{table:chess pieces/az}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Verb====\n{{head|az|verb form}}\n\n# {{inflection of|az|atmaq||2|s|imp}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:az:ADIL|vol=1|page=156}}\n<references/>\n\n==Central Bikol==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{bor+|bcl|tl|at}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{bcl-IPA}}\n\n===Conjunction===\n{{bcl-head|conjunction|b=+}}\n\n# {{lb|bcl|Daet}} [[and]]\n#: {{syn|bcl|asin|saka|buda|sagkod|nan|tapos}}\n\n==Central Puebla Nahuatl==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|ncx|noun|inanimate}}\n\n# [[water]]\n\n==Chuukese==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|chk|noun}}\n\n# [[boy]]\n\n==Crimean Tatar==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|crh|trk-pro|*at}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|crh|noun}}\n\n# [[horse]]\n\n====Declension====\n{{crh-decl|a|q}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:crh:Luğatçıq}}\n\n{{C|crh|Equids}}\n\n==Danish==\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{inh|da|non|at}}. Cognate with {{cog|sv|att}}, {{cog|no|at}}. Probably from {{inh|da|gem-pro|*þat}}, a demonstrative pronoun used as a conjunction; compare {{cog|en|that}}, {{cog|de|dass}}, {{cog|nl|dat}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|da|/ad/|[æ(d̥)]|[æ(t)]}}\n\n====Conjunction====\n{{head|da|conjunction}}\n\n# [[that]] {{q|introduces a {{glossary|noun clause}} functioning as the subject, object or predicative of a verb, or as the object of a prepositional phrase}}\n#* {{quote-text|da|year=1986|author=Knud Erik Larsen|title=Bare ikke om søndagen|url=https://books.google.dk/books?id=DedIDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT85\n|passage=Knud hørte, '''at''' bedstefaren lagde værktøjet fra sig\n|translation=Knud heard '''that''' his grandfather put down the tool.}}\n#* {{quote-book|da|year=1876|author=J.P. Jacobsen|title=Fru Marie Grubbe|volume=1|page=67|url=https://books.google.dk/books?id=VdK9DgAAQBAJ&pg=PT59\n|passage=Hun var overbevist om '''at''' det var sandt.\n|translation=She was convinced '''that''' it was true.}}\n# {{lb|da|archaic}} [[that]], [[in order that]], [[so that]] {{q|introduces an {{glossary|adverbial clause}} stating the purpose}}\n#* '''1856''', Christian Winther, ''Hr. Peder Jernskjæg'', from ''Hjortens Flugt'' / https://kalliope.org/da/text/winther2018100610:\n#*: Og Hjorten vil jeg fange, | At Korset jeg kan faae.\n#*:: And the deer, I will catch, that I may win the cross.\n#* {{quote-text|da|year=1987|author=Thomas Bruun|title=Et paradisisk blik. Humoresker og grotesker\n|passage=det er helvedes svært, '''at''' du bare ved det.\n|translation=it is damned difficult, just '''that''' you know it.}}\n#: {{synonyms|da|for at}}\n# [[that]], [[so that]] {{q|introduces an {{glossary|adverbial clause}} stating the result, normally after a demonstrative adverb or pronoun}}\n#* {{quote-text|da|year=1902|author=Karin Michaëlis|title=Barnet|url=https://books.google.dk/books?id=A_4kDgAAQBAJ&pg=PT62\n|passage=Jeg er saa fattig, '''at''' jeg sulter paa Sjæl og Legeme.\n|translation=I am so poor '''that''' I starve in my soul and my body.}}\n#: {{synonyms|da|så at|således at}}\n# [[that]], [[why]] {{q|introducing an {{glossary|independent clause}}, expressing passion, surprise, anger, or joy}}\n#* {{quote-text|da|year=1901|author=Herman Bang|title=Det graa Hus|url=https://books.google.dk/books?id=xpqmDgAAQBAJ&pg=PT26\n|passage='''At''' De kan synge saa tidligt om Morgenen.\n|translation='''That''' you can sing that early in the morning.}}\n# {{lb|da|proscribed}} {{non-gloss|added pleonastically to other conjunctions: {{l|da|fordi|fordi at}}, {{l|da|hvis|hvis at}}, {{l|da|når|når at}}}}\n#* '''2009''', Frank Colding, Sejleren, p. 32 / https://books.google.dk/books?id=HCNperkZeKIC&pg=PA32:\n#*: Forbavset aner min forstand, | at denne scenes sære magt | kun begribes, '''hvis at''' man | bevæger sig i dansetakt.\n#*:: Astonished, my mind senses that the strange power of this scene can only be understood '''if''' one moves in dance steps.\n\n====References====\n* {{R:DDO|at,1}}\n* {{R:ODS online|at,1}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{inh|da|non|at}}, cognate with {{cog|sv|att}}, {{cog|no|å}}. Originally the same word as the preposition {{inh|da|non|at||at, to}}, from {{inh|da|gem-pro|*at}}, cognate with {{cog|en|at}}. {{doublet|da|ad}}). In the West Germanic languages, a different preposition, {{m|gem-pro|*tō||to}}, serves as the infinitive marker, cf {{cog|en|to}}, {{cog|de|zu}}, {{cog|nl|te}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|da|[ʌ]|[ɒ̽]}}\n* {{q|at the beginning of a sentence}} {{IPA|da|[ʌ]|[ɒ̽]|/ad/|[æt]}}\n* {{homophones|da|og}}\n\n====Particle====\n{{head|da|particle}}\n\n# [[to]] {{q|infinitive-marker, obligatory when the infinitive functions as noun phrase or an adverbial phrase, but omitted when it is governed by a modal verb}}\n#: {{ux|da|Det er menneskeligt '''at''' fejle.|It is human '''to''' fail.}}\n# {{non-gloss|introducing an adverb of direction after a phrase that normally governs an infinitive (which may be understood {{glossary|ellipsis|elliptically}})}}\n#* {{quote-text|da|year=1992|author=Thøger Birkeland|title=Bette Nielses krig\n|passage=Mon de da ikke snart skulle til '''at''' hjemad!\n|translation=Aren't they going to go home soon!}}\n\n====References====\n* {{R:DDO|at,2}}\n* {{R:ODS online|at,2}}\n\n==Dutch==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|nl|/ɑt/}}\n* {{audio|nl|Nl-at.ogg}}\n* {{rhymes|nl|ɑt|s=1}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|nl|verb form}}\n\n# {{infl of|nl|eten||s|past|ind}}\n# {{infl of|nl|atten||bare-ten-verb}}\n\n==Eastern Durango Nahuatl==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|azd|noun}}\n\n# [[water]]\n\n==Egyptian==\n\n===Romanization===\n{{head|egy|romanization}}\n\n# {{egy-alt tr|ꜥt|type=Manuel de Codage}}\n\n==Faroese==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|fo|/ɛaːʰt/}}\n* {{rhymes|fo|ɛaːʰt}}\n* {{homophones|fo|æt}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{der|fo|non|at}}.\n\n====Preposition====\n{{head|fo|preposition}}\n\n# {{l|en|at}}, [[towards]], [[to]] {{+obj|fo|dat}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{der|fo|non|at||that}}, from {{der|fo|gem-pro|*þat||that}}. Cognate with {{cog|enm|at||pos=conjunction and relative pronoun|that}}, {{cog|sco|at||pos=conjunction and relative pronoun|that}}. More at {{l|en|that}}.\n\n====Conjunction====\n{{head|fo|conjunction}}\n\n# [[that]]\n\n===Etymology 3===\nFrom {{der|fo|non|at||at, to}}, from {{der|fo|gem-pro|*at||at, to}}. More at {{l|en|at}}.\n\n====Particle====\n{{head|fo|particle}}\n\n# [[to]] {{non-gloss|A particle used to mark the following verb as an [[infinitive]].}}\n#: {{ux|fo|'''At''' lyfta.|inline=1|To lift}}\n\n==Friulian==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{der|fur|la|actus}}. Cognate with {{cog|it|atto}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{fur-noun|m}}\n\n# [[act]], [[action]], [[deed]]\n\n====Related terms====\n* {{l|fur|azion}}\n\n==German==\n\n===Etymology 1===\nBorrowed from {{bor|de|en|at|id=sign}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|de|/ɛt/}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{de-noun|n,-,s}}\n\n# [[#English|at]], [[at-sign]]\n#: {{syn|de|at-Zeichen|Klammeraffe}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Symbol====\n{{head|de|symbol}}\n\n# {{lb|de|dated|physics}} Symbol for {{m|de|technisch|technische}} {{m|de|Atmosphäre}}, a non-[[SI]] unit of [[pressure]] used until 1978.\n#: {{cot|de|atü|Pascal}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:de:Duden|at_in_E_Mail_Adressen}}\n* {{R:de:Duden|at_Einheit_Druck_Atmosphaere}}\n* {{R:de:DWDS}}\n\n==Gothic==\n\n===Romanization===\n{{got-rom}}\n\n# {{romanization of|got|𐌰𐍄}}\n\n==Hokkien==\n{{zh-see|遏|poj|to [[snap]] something off; to [[break]] something; etc.}}\n\n==Icelandic==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{rfe|is}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|is|/aːt/}}\n* {{rhymes|is|aːt|s=1}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{is-noun|@@}}\n\n# [[fight]]\n\n====Declension====\n{{is-ndecl|n}}\n\n==Irish==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|ga|a=Munster,Aran|/ɑt̪ˠ/|ref={{R:ga:Finck|II|11}}}}\n* {{IPA|ga|a=CF|/at̪ˠ/|[aːt̪ˠ]|ref2={{R:ga:ICF|128|page=26}}}}\n* {{IPA|ga|a=Mayo,Ulster|/at̪ˠ/|ref={{R:ga:Quiggin|117|339}}}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{inh|ga|sga|att||swelling, protuberance, tumour}}.<ref>{{R:DIL|4925|head=att}}</ref>\n\n====Noun====\n{{ga-noun|m|ait|vngen=ata|atanna}}\n\n# [[swelling]]\n#* {{RQ:ga:Finck|II|11|passage=''tā '''at''' ə l̄āv m inīnə.''|t=My daughter has a swelling on her hand.|norm=Tá '''at''' i lámh m’iníne.}}\n#* {{RQ:ga:Finck|II|11|passage=''tā šȧxt '''n-at''' i n-ə wunāl.''|t=He has seven swellings on his neck.|norm=Tá seacht '''n-at''' ina mhuineál.}}\n#* {{RQ:ga:Finck|II|11|passage=''kiŕ də lāv ə n̄-isḱə leš n̥ '''t-at''' ə wȳlū.''|translation=Put your hand in water to reduce the swelling.|norm=Cuir do lámh in uisce leis an '''t-at''' a maolú.}}\n# {{verbal noun of|ga|at}}\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{ga-decl-m1|a|t|it|pl=tanna|strong=yes}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{inh|ga|sga|attaid||pos=v|swells, dilates, increases}}, from {{m|sga|att||swelling, protuberance, tumour}}.<ref>{{R:DIL|4929|head=attaid}}</ref>\n\n====Verb====\n{{head|ga|verbs|present|atann|future|atfaidh|verbal noun|at|past participle|ata}}\n\n# {{lb|ga|intransitive}} [[swell]]\n#: {{syn|ga|borr}}\n#* {{RQ:ga:Finck|II|11|passage=''tā ə h-ēdn̥ '''atī'''.''|t=Her face is swollen.|norm=Tá a héadan '''ataithe'''.}}\n#* {{RQ:ga:Finck|II|11|passage=''tā mə lāv '''atī'''.''|t=My hand is swollen.|norm=Tá mo lámh '''ataithe'''.}}\n# {{lb|ga|intransitive}} [[bloat]]\n# {{lb|ga|intransitive|of sea}} [[heave]]\n\n=====Conjugation=====\n{{ga-conj-1a|a||t|broad|vn=at}}\n* Alternative past participle: {{l|ga|ataithe}}\n\n===Mutation===\n{{ga-mut}}\n\n===References===\n<references/>\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:ga:Ó Dónaill}}\n* {{R:ga:Dinneen|ed=2|p=63}}\n* {{R:ga:Dinneen|ed=2|w=ataim|p=63}}\n* {{R:ga:NEID}}\n\n==Kapampangan==\n\n===Etymology===\nCompare {{cog|pag|ta}} and {{m|pag|tan}}, {{cog|agv|at}}, {{cog|tl|at}}, {{cog|ms|dan}}, {{cog|id|dan}}, {{cog|haw|a}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{pam-IPA}}\n\n===Conjunction===\n{{head|pam|conjunction}}\n\n# [[and]]\n#: {{syn|pam|saka|ampo|atsaka|pati|mo|man}}\n#: {{ux|pam|Pakibilisan '''at''' bawal mabagal.|Do it faster '''and''' stop being slow.}}\n\n===Preposition===\n{{head|pam|preposition}}\n\n# [[with]]\n#: {{ux|pam|Mapagpasubuk '''at''' alang pamagkakelanganan.|to be a challenger '''with''' no hesitations.}}\n\n==Ladin==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{der|lld|la|actus}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{lld-noun|m|ac}}\n\n# [[act]]\n# [[action]]\n# [[work]]\n\n==Latin==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{la-IPA}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{inh|la|itc-pro|*ati}}, from {{inh|la|ine-pro|*h₂et-|*h₂éti}}.\n\n====Conjunction====\n{{head|la|conjunctions}}\n\n# {{ng|introduces a different but not completely opposing thought:}} [[but]], [[yet]], [[moreover]], on the [[other]] [[hand]], on the [[contrary]], [[still]]\n#* {{Q|la|Virgil|Aeneid|4|1|quote='''At''' rēgīna [...].|trans='''''But''' the Queen [...].''<br/>(This phrase, which begins Book 4, recurs twice more to begin subsections within the book: cf. 4.296, 4.504.)}}\n#* {{quote-book|la|year=1772|title=Historia Ecclesiastica Islandiæ|trans-title=The Ecclesiastical History of Iceland|author=[[w:Finnur Jónsson (bishop)|Finnur Jónsson]]|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6bwFAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA9&hl=de&source=gbs_selected_pages&cad=1#v=onepage&q&f=false|volume=1|location=Copenhagen|publisher=Orphanotrophius Regii|page=3|chapter=1|section=4|text=[[hoc|Hoc]] [[seculo|Seculo]] [[quinto|qvinto]] [[factum]] [[esse|eſſe]] [[oportet]], [[cum]] [[certum]] [[sit|ſit]], [[Hengistum|Hengiſtum]] [[tunc]] [[temporis]] [[floruisse|floruiſſe]]; '''at''' [[fides]] [[tamen]] [[hujus]] [[rei]] [[penes]] [[Authorem]] [[esto|eſto]].|norm=hōc sēculō quīntō factum esse oportet, cum certum sit, Hengistum tunc temporis flōruisse; at fidēs tamen hujus reī penes authōrem estō|t=It must be that this occurred in the fifth century, since it is certain that Hengist flourished at that time; '''but''', nevertheless, let the credibility of this matter rest with the author.}}\n# [[whereas]]\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{l|la|ast}}\n* {{l|la|sed}}\n* {{l|la|tamen}} {{qualifier|postpositive}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|la|atquī}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nAlternative spelling of {{m|la|ad}}. See [[aliquit#Etymology]].\n\n====Preposition====\n{{la-prep|at|accusative}}\n\n# {{alternative spelling of|la|ad|t=towards, to}}\n#* {{Q|la|Iovianus Pontanus|[[s:la:Hendecasyllaborum seu Baiarum libri duo/1.30|Hendecasyllaborum seu Baiarum libri duo]]|1|30|26|year=1490-1500|quote=At '''te''' balneolae tuae bearunt,}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:la:L&S}}\n* {{R:la:Elementary Lewis}}\n* {{R:la:du Cange}}\n* {{R:itc:EDL}}\n\n==Livonian==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alter|liv|attõ|āt|ātõ}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|liv|verb form}}\n\n# {{verb form of|liv|vȱlda||3|p|pres|ind}}\n\n==Middle English==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{etymon|enm|id=on|:inh|ang:æt<id:place>}}\nFrom {{inh|enm|ang|æt}}, from {{inh|enm|gem-pro|*at}}, from {{inh|enm|ine-pro|*h₂éd}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alter|enm|et|ed}}\n\n====Preposition====\n{{head|enm|preposition}}\n\n# [[#English|at]]\n\n=====Descendants=====\n* {{desc|en|at}}\n* {{desc|sco|at}}\n* {{desc|yol|adh|alts=1}}\n\n=====References=====\n* {{R:MED Online|at|prep|MED2734}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{bor|enm|non|at}}.\n\n====Particle====\n{{head|enm|particle}}\n\n# {{lb|enm|Northern|NEM}} [[to]] {{gl|infinitive-marker}}\n\n=====References=====\n* {{R:MED Online|at|adv|MED2735}}\n\n==Middle Welsh==\n\n===Etymology===\nVariant of {{der|wlm|owl|ad}}, from {{der|wlm|cel-pro|*ad-|*ad}}, from {{der|wlm|ine-pro|*h₂éd}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|wlm|/at/}}\n\n===Preposition===\n{{h|wlm|prep}}\n\n# [[to]], [[towards]]\n\n====Inflection====\n{{wlm-infl-prep\n|1s=attaf\n|2s=attat\n|3m=attaw\n|3f=attei//etti\n|1p=attam//attan//attom\n|2p=attawch\n|3p=attaðunt//attunt\n}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:wlm:Evans|page=59|section=§&nbsp;63&nbsp;(a)}}\n\n==North Frisian==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n\n====Article====\n{{head|frr|article}} {{lb|frr|Föhr-Amrum}}\n\n# [[the]] {{q|feminine and neuter definite article, reduced form}}\n#: {{coordinate terms|frr|det|q=full form}}\n\n=====Usage notes=====\n* The article form {{m|frr||at}} can be used with all feminine and neuter nouns. However, some original feminines may still take the older form {{m|frr|a}} (otherwise now restricted to masculines). This group of feminines consists of a limited number of everyday words, including (but not restricted to) those for relatives, body parts and items of clothing. The article {{m|frr||a}} is used with these especially when the sense is either [[possessive]] or [[generic]] (i.e. referring to a thing as such without regard to any particular item). For example: {{m|frr||Hi hee '''a''' hun breegen.|t=He broke the [i.e. his] hand.}} {{m|fr||At wiar so stal üüs uun '''a''' sark.|t=It was so silent as at the [i.e. any] church.}}\n\n=====Alternative forms=====\n* {{alt|frr|e|et||Mooring}}\n\n=====See also=====\n{{frr-Foehr-articles}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Pronoun====\n{{head|frr|pronoun}} {{lb|frr|Föhr-Amrum}}\n\n# {{form of|frr|Reduced form|hat|t=it|pos=subject}}\n# {{form of|frr|Reduced form|ham|t=it|pos=object}}\n\n=====Usage notes=====\n* The form {{m|frr||at}} is always unstressed, but not necessarily [[enclitic]] like other reduced forms.\n\n=====Alternative forms=====\n* {{alt|frr|'t||enclitic}}\n* {{alt|frr|et||Mooring|Sylt}}\n\n=====See also=====\n{{frr-personal pronouns/Foehr}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\nFrom {{inh|frr|ofs|*jit}}, from {{inh|frr|gmw-pro|*jit|t=you two}}. Regarding the Sylt Frisian forms {{m|frr||at|t=the two of you}} versus {{m|frr|jat|t=the two of them}}, it is clear that {{m|frr||jat}} became at some point associated with {{m|frr|[[ja]], [[jam]], [[jaar]]|t=they, them, their}}. For a while {{m|frr||jat}} must have had both senses, which was facilitated by the general overlap between second-person and third-person plural forms in North Frisian; compare {{m|frr|jam}}, which means “them” on Sylt, “you [plural]” on Föhr and Amrum, and both of these in Mooring Frisian. The form {{m|frr||at}} may have been originally an enclitic byform of {{m|frr||jat}}, or may have been backformed later to reintroduce a distinction between second and third person.\n\n====Pronoun====\n{{head|frr|pronoun}} {{lb|frr|Sylt|dated}}\n\n# [[you]] [[two]], the two of you {{gloss|second-person dual personal pronoun}}\n\n=====Alternative forms=====\n* {{alt|frr|jat||Föhr-Amrum|Mooring|both [[obsolete]]}}\n\n=====See also=====\n{{frr-personal pronouns/Sylt}}\n\n==Norwegian Bokmål==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{der|nb|non|at}}. Cognate with {{cog|da|at}} and {{cog|sv|att}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|nb|/at/|[ɑt]}}\n\n===Conjunction===\n{{head|nb|conjunction}}\n\n# [[that#Conjunction|that]]\n\n===References===\n{{R:nb:OB}}\n\n==Norwegian Nynorsk==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{der|nn|non|at}}. Cognate with {{cog|da|at}} and {{cog|sv|att}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|nn|/ɑtː/}}\n* {{homophones|nn|att}}\n\n===Conjunction===\n{{head|nn|conjunction}}\n\n# [[that#Conjunction|that]]\n\n===References===\n{{R:nn:OB}}\n\n==Old Dutch==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|odt|gmw-pro|*āt}}, from {{inh|odt|gem-pro|*ētą}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{odt-noun|head=āt|n}}\n\n# [[food]]\n\n====Declension====\n{{odt-decl-noun-a|āt|g=n}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|odt|āton}}\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desc|dum|âet}}\n** {{desc|nl|aat}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:ONW|1265|āt}}\n\n==Old Irish==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alter|sga|it||second-person singular}}\n* {{alter|sga|ata||third-person plural relative}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{sense|second-person singular}} {{sga-IPA|att.}}\n* {{sense|third-person plural relative}} {{sga-IPA|at.}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|sga|verb form}}\n\n# {{inflection of|sga|is||2|s|pres|indc|;|3|p|pres|indc|relative}}\n\n==Old Norse==\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{inh|non|gem-pro|*atą}}. Related to {{cog|non|etja}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{non-noun|n|ats|ǫt}}\n\n# [[conflict]], [[fight]], [[battle]]\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{non-decl-n-a|at|ǫt}}\n\n=====Descendants=====\n* {{desc|is|at}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{inh|non|gem-pro|*þat||that}}. Cognate with {{cog|ang|þæt}}, {{cog|got|𐌸𐌰𐍄𐌰}}. Doublet of {{m|non|þat}}; for similar loss of ''þ-'' compare {{m|non|an|id=than}} from {{ncog|gem-pro|*þan}}.\n\n====Conjunction====\n{{head|non|conjunction}}\n\n# {{senseid|non|that}} [[that]]\n# [[since]], [[because]], [[as]]\n\n=====Descendants=====\n{{top2}}\n* {{desc|is|að}}\n* {{desc|fo|at}}\n* {{desc|no|at}}\n* {{desc|sv|att}}\n* {{desc|da|at}}\n{{bottom}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\nFrom {{inh|non|gem-pro|*at||at, to}}. Cognate with {{cog|ang|æt}}, {{cog|ofs|et}}, {{cog|osx|at}}, {{cog|goh|az}}, {{cog|got|𐌰𐍄}}.\n\n====Particle====\n{{head|non|particle}}\n\n# [[to]] {{gloss|infinitive particle}}\n\n=====Descendants=====\n{{top2}}\n* {{desc|is|að}}\n* {{desc|fo|at}}\n* Norwegian:\n** {{desc|nb|å}}\n** {{desc|nn|å}}\n* {{desc|sv|att}}\n* {{desc|da|at}}\n{{bottom}}\n\n====Preposition====\n{{head|non|preposition}}\n\n# {{l|en|at}}, [[to]] {{+obj|non|dat}}\n# [[according to]] {{+obj|non|dat}}\n#: {{ux|non|'''at''' heiðnum lǫgum|'''according to''' heathen law}}\n# [[from]], when acquiring something {{+obj|non|dat}}\n#: {{ux|non|hann þá mjǫð '''at''' goðum|he received mead '''from''' the gods}}\n#: {{ux|non|ek nam frǿði '''at''' Snorra|I learned wisdom '''from''' Snorri}}\n\n=====Descendants=====\n{{top2}}\n* {{desc|is|að}}\n* {{desc|fo|at}}\n* {{desc|nn|åt}}\n* {{desc|gmq-osw|at|āt}}\n** {{desc|sv|åt}}\n* {{desc|gmq-oda|at}}\n** {{desc|da|ad}}\n*** {{desc|nb|ad}}\n{{bottom}}\n\n====Further reading====\n* {{R:non:Zoega}}\n\n===Etymology 4===\nFrom earlier {{m|non|apt}}, from {{inh|non|gmq-pro|ᚨᚠᛏᛖᚱ}}, {{m|gmq-pro|ᛡᚠᚨᛏᛉ|ts=afᵃtr}}. Related to {{m|non|eptir}}, {{m|non|ept}}.\n\n====Preposition====\n{{head|non|preposition}}\n\n# [[after]], [[following]], [[in memory of]] {{+obj|non|acc}}\n#* Hávamál\n#: {{ux|non|sjaldan bautarsteinar · standa brautu nær<br/>nema reisi niðr '''at''' nið|menhirs [do] seldom stand near the road, unless a kinsman raise one '''in memory of''' a kinsman}}\n#* Grágás\n#*: {{quote|non|sonr á at taka arf '''at''' fǫður sinn|the son ought to take inheritance '''after''' his father}}\n\n==Pipil==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{der|ppl|azc-nah-pro|*aa-|*aa-tl}}, from {{der|ppl|azc-pro|*pa|*pa-ta}}. Compare {{cog|nci|ātl||water}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|ppl|/at/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{ppl-noun|pl=ahat}}\n\n# [[water]]\n#: {{ux|ppl|Xiconi chopi '''at'''|Drink some '''water'''}}\n# [[rain]]\n#: {{ux|ppl|Axcan huetzi '''at'''|Today it's '''rain'''ing}}\n# [[river]]\n#: {{ux|ppl|Nemi ne tacat itempan ne '''at'''|The man is on the '''river'''bank}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col3|ppl|ayo<alt:-ayo><t:soup, broth; juice; liquid>\n}}\n\n==Pnar==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|pbv|aav-khs-pro|*ʔa:t}}, from {{der|pbv|mkh-pro|*as|*as ~ ʔəs}}. Cognate with {{cog|kha|at}}, {{cog|ril|-}} [Sak] ''ʔas¹'', {{cog|nev|-}} ''ʔaːjh'', {{cog|pac|ayh}}, {{cog|sea|as}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|pbv|/at/}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|pbv|verb}}\n\n# to [[swell]]\n\n==Pochutec==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{der|xpo|azc-nah-pro|*aa-|*aa-tl}}, from {{der|xpo|azc-pro|*pa|*pa-ta}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|xpo|/ˈat/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|xpo|noun}}\n\n# {{l|en|water}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:Boas 1917}}\n* {{R:Knab 1980}}\n\n==Salar==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|slr|trk-pro|*at}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|slr|[ˀɑ̥tʰ]|a=Xunhua,Hualong,Qinghai|ref=Lianyun (1985): p. 5 !!! Dywer (2007): pp. 188, 191-192 !!! Kunlun (2015): p. 44, 292}}\n* {{IPA|slr|/ɑtʰ/|a=Ili,Xinjiang|ref=Yakup (2002): p. 42}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{slr-noun|ı|lar}}\n\n# [[horse]]\n\n====Declension====\n{{slr-decl-noun}}\n{{slr-poss-decl}}\n\n===References===\n<references/>\n* {{R:slr:Potanin|ат|page=428}}\n* {{R:slr:Stroy|page=296}}\n* {{R:slr:Lianyun|page=5}}\n* {{R:slr:Yakup|page=47}}\n* {{R:slr:Dwyer|page=45, 106, 180}}\n* {{R:slr:MaChengjun|page=22}}\n* {{R:slr:Kunlun|page=44, 292}}\n* {{R:slr:MaWei2|page=263}}\n\n{{C|slr|Equids}}\n\n==Scots==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{etymon|sco|:inh|enm:at<id:on>}}\nFrom {{inh|sco|enm|at|id=on}}.\n\n====Preposition====\n{{h|sco|prep}}\n\n# {{l|en|at}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Pronoun====\n{{head|sco|pronoun}}\n\n# {{lb|sco|especially|Black Isle}} [[what]]\n# [[that]] (which)\n\n====References====\n* '''2018''', Robert McColl Millar, ''[https://www.google.com/books/edition/Modern_Scots/XtdJEAAAQBAJ Modern Scots]: An Analytical Survey'', pages 13-14:\n*: [The] Scots dialects of the Black Isle, a promontory to the north of Inverness, were largely confined to two villages, Cromarty and Avoch, which are not fully connected to the North- East Scots- speaking regions to the east of Inverness {{...}} The Black Isle dialects (North Northern B) shared much with their Caithness equivalents. With one feature, however, they stood alone, not only in the North or even Scotland, but in the English-speaking world. {{...|The loss of /h/ in all positions is a very unusual feature anywhere north of the River Tyne in the North-East of England; indeed it is essentially peculiar to the Black Isle. What is much more striking for that region, however, is that}} the &lt;wh&gt; words were not replaced by /f/, as is the case with the other Northern dialects, but by ''nothing''. The Scots equivalent to English ''what'', which is ''fit'' or ''fat'' in the rest of the Scots-speaking North, was ''at'' in Cromarty and Avoch. {{...}} a good case could be made for the last speaker of archetypically 'Black Isle Scots' dying in 2012.\n\n==Scottish Gaelic==\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{inh|gd|sga|att}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{gd-noun|g=m}}\n\n# [[swelling]], [[tumour]]\n# [[protuberance]], [[prominence]]\n# {{verbal noun of|gd|at}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col3\n|gd|{{l|gd|at-bràghad||quinsy; tonsillitis}}\n|{{l|gd|at-chuisle||aneurysm}}\n|{{l|gd|at-fhuachd||chilblain}}\n|{{l|gd|at-reum||swelling in the back of the mouth}}\n}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{inh|gd|sga|attaid||pos=v|swells, dilates, increases}}, from {{m|sga|att||swelling, protuberance, tumour}}.\n\n====Verb====\n{{head|gd|verb|past|dh'at|future|ataidh|verbal noun|at|or|atadh|past participle|athte}}\n\n# [[swell]], [[fester]], [[puff up]], become [[tumid]]\n# swell, as in the sea\n\n===Mutation===\n{{gd-mut-vowel}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:Dwelly}}\n* {{R:DIL|4925|head=att}}\n* {{R:DIL|4929|head=attaid}}\n\n==Selaru==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{der|slu|poz-cet-pro|*əpat}}, from {{der|slu|poz-pro|*əpat}}, from {{der|slu|map-pro|*Səpat}}.\n\n===Numeral===\n{{head|slu|numeral}}\n\n# {{cln|slu|cardinal numbers}} {{l|en|four}}\n\n{{topics|slu|Four}}\n\n==Serbo-Croatian==\n\n===Etymology===\nBorrowed from {{bor|sh|ota|آت|tr=at}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{sh-noun||m-an}}\n\n# [[steed]]\n# [[Arabian]] {{q|horse}}\n\n====Declension====\n{{sh-decl-noun\n|at|ati / atovi / atlari\n|ata|ata / atova / atlara\n|atu|atima / atovima / atlarima\n|ata|ate / atove / atlare\n|ate|ati / atovi / atlari\n|atu|atima / atovima / atlarima\n|atom|atima / atovima / atlarima\n}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col4|sh|atkinja|atlija|atmejdan|atski}}\n\n==Simeulue==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{der|smr|poz-pro|*əpat}}, from {{der|smr|map-pro|*Səpat}}.\n\n===Numeral===\n{{head|smr|numeral}}\n\n# {{cln|smr|cardinal numbers}} {{l|en|four}}\n\n{{topics|smr|Four}}\n\n==Sougb==\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|mnx|verb}}\n\n# [[hit]]\n\n====Declension====\n{{mnx-conj-a}}\n\n===References===\n* ''A Grammar Sketch of Sougb'', in ''Languages of the Eastern Bird's Head'' (2002)\n\n==Tagalog==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|tl|'t||after words ending with vowel}}\n\n===Etymology===\nCompare {{cog|pag|ta||because}} and {{m|pag|tan||and}}, and {{cog|agv|at||and; because}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{tl-pr}}\n\n===Conjunction===\n{{tl-head|conjunction|b=+}}\n\n# [[and]]\n#: {{syn|tl|saka|pati}}\n# [[as]]; [[for]]; [[because]]\n#: {{syn|tl|dahil|kasi}}\n#: {{ux|tl|Bilisan mo '''at''' ako'y aalis na.|Do it faster, '''as''' I'm leaving soon.}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col|tl|at saka|at ano|ngunit|subalit|bawat|kahit|datapwat|bagamat|bakit|kahimat|kahinyamat|mayapat}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|tl|a=at|ta}}\n\n==Tlingit==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|tli|[ʔʌ̀tʰ]}}\n\n===Pronoun===\n{{head|tli|pronoun}}\n\n# fourth-person non-human object pronoun (roughly equivalent to \"[[something]]\")\n# fourth-person non-human possessive pronoun (roughly equivalent to \"something's\")\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col4|tli\n|at ashoowatán\n|at áatʼláni\n|at chʼéx̱ʼdi\n|at danáayi\n|at dáli\n|at daakayéx̱aa lítaa\n|at daayí\n|at daayí ḵákw\n|at daa.ideidí\n|at dultʼéexʼ\n|at duxáshgu\n|at gutu.ádi\n|at gutú\n|at éewu\n|at kachʼáakʼu\n|at kahéeni\n|at kasayé\n|at katáxʼaa\n|at katé\n|at kax̱útʼti\n|at ka.áax̱u\n|at káx̱ adéli\n|at kaawaxúkw\n|at kaayí\n|at kuna.áaḵw\n|at kookeidí\n|at kʼé\n|at layeix̱ sʼaatí\n|at la.át\n|at luxʼaaḵáawu\n|at natéeyi\n|at sag̱ahaayí\n|at sax̱án\n|at sʼaan.ax̱w dzáas\n|at sʼéilʼi\n|at shax̱ishdi dzáas\n|at shí\n|at shí ḵóok\n|at sheexʼí\n|at sheeyí\n|at shooḵ\n|at tugáni\n|at tux̱ʼwánsʼ\n|at tʼaa.éexʼi\n|at tsʼíkʼwti\n|at uhéini\n|at wujaaḵw\n|at wulyáaḵw\n|at wulyú\n|at wuskú yís át ḵuwduwateen\n|at wuskóowu\n|at wooskú daakahídi\n|at xáshdi téel\n|at xáshdi xʼóow\n|at xʼaan aaní\n|at xʼaan hídi\n|at x̱aagú shakee.át\n|at x̱ʼawóosʼ\n|at x̱ʼéeshi\n|at yahaayí xʼúxʼ kshaxeet\n|at yana.á\n|at yawusḵá\n|at yátxʼi daa yoo at kooneik ḵáa\n|at yáa awuné\n|atkʼátskʼu\n|atxaayí\n|atx̱a át\n|atx̱á\n|atx̱aaxʼí sáani\n|atyátxʼi\n|at.óow\n}}\n\n==Tocharian B==\n\n===Etymology===\nAn apocopated form of {{m|txb|ate||id}}\n\n===Adverb===\n{{head|txb|adverb}}\n\n# [[away]]\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:txb:Adams 2013|head=at|page=9}}\n\n==Torres Strait Creole==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{der|tcs|en|heart}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|tcs|noun}}\n\n# [[heart]]\n\n{{topics|tcs|Anatomy}}\n\n==Turkish==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{tr-IPA||[ˈɑt]}}\n* {{audio|tr|Tur-at.ogg}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{inh|tr|ota|آت||tr=at|horse}}, from {{inh|tr|trk-pro|*at}}, {{m|trk-pro|*ăt||horse}}. Cognate with {{cog|xqa|اَتْ||tr=at|horse}}, {{cog|otk|𐱃||ts=at|horse}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{tr-noun|ı|lar}}\n\n# [[horse]]\n#: {{syn|tr|beygir|düldül}}\n# {{lb|tr|chess}} [[knight]]\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{tr-infl-noun-c|a|pred=1|poss=1}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col3|tr|atlı|atsız|atlanmak|atla deve değil|at hırsızı|atçı|atlıkarınca|at gibi|at gözlüğü|at at oluncaya kadar sahibi mat olur|at arabası|at bakıcısı|at beslenirken kız istenirken|at binenin, kılıç kuşananın|at binicisine göre kişner|at bulunur meydan bulunmaz, meydan bulunur at bulunmaz|at cambazı|at çalındıktan sonra ahırın kapısını kapamak|at donu|at izi it izine karışmak|at ile avrat yiğidin bahtına|at yedi günde, it yediği günde|at yiğidin yoldaşıdır|at olur, meydan olmaz; meydan olur, at olmaz|at oynatmak|at sineği|at kestanesi|at koşturmak|at var, meydan yok|at nalı|at meydanı|atkuyruğu}}\n\n====See also====\n{{table:chess pieces/tr}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Verb====\n{{head|tr|verb form}}\n\n# {{tr-verb form of|atmak}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:tr:TDK}}\n\n{{C|tr|Equids}}\n\n==Turkmen==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{tk-variant|c=ат|l=at|a=آت}}\n\nFrom {{inh|tk|trk-pro|*at}}, {{m|trk-pro|*ăt||horse}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|tk|/ɑt/}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{tk-noun|aty|lar}}\n\n# [[horse]]\n# {{lb|tk|chess}} [[knight]]\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{tk-decl-noun-auto|a|c}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{tk-variant|c=ат|l=at|a=آد}}\n\nFrom {{inh|tk|trk-pro|*āt||name}}. Cognate with {{cog|otk|𐰀𐱃||name}}, {{cog|cv|ят||name}}, {{cog|tr|ad}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|tk|/ɑːt/}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{tk-noun|head=āt|ādy|lar}}\n\n# [[name]]\n# [[nickname]]\n# [[noun]]\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{tk-decl-noun-auto|head=āt|a|c|stem=ād}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:tk:Enedilim}}\n* {{R:tk:webonary}}\n\n==Volapük==\n\n===Determiner===\n{{head|vo|determiner}}\n\n# {{lb|vo|demonstrative}} [[this]]\n#* {{quote-book|vo|1931|Arie de Jong|Gramat Volapüka, § 256|text=Kaf '''at''' binon naudodik.|t='''This''' coffee is disgusting.}}\n\n==Wakhi==\n\n===Etymology===\nCognate with {{cog|yai|ашт}}.\n\n===Numeral===\n{{head|wbl|numeral}}\n\n# [[eight]]\n\n==Welsh==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{der|cy|wlm|at}}, variant of {{inh|cy|owl|ad}} (alongside the now-obsolete {{m|cy|add}}), from {{inh|cy|cel-pro|*ad-|*ad}}, from {{inh|cy|ine-pro|*h₂éd}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|cy|/at/}}\n* {{rhymes|cy|at|s=1}}\n\n===Preposition===\n{{head|cy|preposition|triggers soft mutation}}\n\n# [[to]], [[towards]]\n# [[for]]\n# {{l|en|at}}\n# [[by]]\n\n====Usage notes====\n* {{m|cy|At}} is often used to indicate direction \"to\" a person in contrast to {{m|cy|i}}, which indicates direction \"to\" a place or \"(in order) to\" do an action.\n** {{uxi|cy|Dw i'n mynd '''at''' y meddyg.|I'm going '''to''' the doctor.}}\n*** but with a place: {{uxi|cy|Dw i'n mynd '''i''''r feddygfa.|I'm going '''to''' the surgery.}}\n*** and also before a verb: {{uxi|cy|Dw i'n mynd '''i''' weld y meddyg.|I'm going '''to''' see the doctor.}}\n** {{uxi|cy|Wnaeth hi anfon llythyr '''at''' Megan.|She sent a letter '''to''' Megan.}}\n*** but with a place: {{uxi|cy|Wnaeth hi anfon llythyr '''i''' Gaerdydd.|She sent a letter '''to''' Cardiff.}}\n*** and also before a verb: {{uxi|cy|Oedd hi'n mynd '''i''' anfon llythyr.|She was going '''to''' send a letter.}}\n:See {{m|cy|oddi wrth}} for a similar distinction for \"from\".\n\n====Inflection====\n{{cy-personal-prep-literary|ataf|atat|ato|ati|atom|atoch|atynt}}\n{{cy-personal-prep-colloquial|[[ato]] [[i]]/[[fi]], [[ata]]|[[atot]] [[ti]], [[atat]]|ato|ati|aton|atoch|atyn}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col|cy\n|agos atoch<t:friendly, intimate>\n|hyd at\n|tuag at<t:towards>\n}}\n* [[:Category:Welsh phrasal verbs formed with \"at\"]]\n\n==West Frisian==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|fy|/ɔt/}}\n\n===Conjunction===\n{{head|fy|conjunction}}\n\n# [[if]]\n#: {{syn|fy|as}}\n\n====Further reading====\n* {{R:WFT|2100}}\n\n==West Makian==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|mqs|/at̪/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|mqs|noun}}\n\n# [[man]]\n# [[male]]\n# [[husband]]\n\n===References===\n* {{R:mqs:Voorhoeve:1982}}\n\n==Wolof==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{audio|wo|Wo-at.ogg}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{wo-noun|mi}}\n\n# [[year]]\n\n{{topics|wo|Years}}\n\n==Yola==\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{inh|yol|enm|that|that, thet, yat}}, from {{inh|yol|ang|þæt}}, from {{inh|yol|gem-pro|*þat}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alter|yol|et|thet|that|th'|y'at}}\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|yol|/at/|/ɛt/|/ðɛt/|/ðat/|/ð/}}\n\n====Pronoun====\n{{head|yol|pronoun}}\n\n# [[that]], [[which]]\n#* {{quote-book|yol|year=1867|page=84|chapter=A YOLA ZONG|number=3|title=SONGS, ETC. IN THE DIALECT OF FORTH AND BARGY|passage='''At''' by mizluck was ee-pit t'drive in.|translation='''Who''' by misluck was placed to drive in.}}\n#* {{quote-book|yol|year=1867|page=86|chapter=A YOLA ZONG|number=5|title=SONGS, ETC. IN THE DIALECT OF FORTH AND BARGY|passage='''At''' aar errone was var ameing 'ar 'ngish ee-height.|translation='''That''' their errand was aiming to bring anguish upon them.}}\n#* {{quote-book|yol|year=1867|chapter=A YOLA ZONG|number=13|page=90|title=SONGS, ETC. IN THE DIALECT OF FORTH AND BARGY|passage=He '''at''' nouth fade t'zey, llean vetch ee man,|translation=He '''that''' knows what to say, mischief fetch the man,}}\n#* {{quote-book|yol|year=1867|chapter=VERSES IN ANSWER TO THE WEDDEEN O BALLYMORE|number=3|page=100|title=SONGS, ETC. IN THE DIALECT OF FORTH AND BARGY|passage='''At''' ye mye ne'er be wooveless ta vill a lear jock an cooan.|translation='''That''' you may never be unprovided to fill an empty jack and can.}}\n#* {{quote-book|yol|year=1867|chapter=THE BRIDE'S PORTION|page=102|title=SONGS, ETC. IN THE DIALECT OF FORTH AND BARGY|passage=Dhree brailès o' beanès, an a keow '''at''' was yole,|translation=Three barrels of beans, and a cow '''that''' was old,}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|yol|'twode}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{inh|yol|enm|at|āt}}, from {{inh|yol|ang|ǣt}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|yol|/at/}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{head|yol|verb form}}\n\n# {{inflection of|yol|ayth||past}}\n#* '''1867''', “GLOSSARY OF THE DIALECT OF FORTH AND BARGY“, page 23:  \n#*: {{quote|yol|Ich '''at''' mee dhree meales.|I '''ate''' my three meals.}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:Poole 1867|page=23}}"}}